I model the Colorado Joint Line from Denver to Pueblo in O Scale (1/48). I have been modeling this line since 1989 in a variety of scales and mediums. My facilities include traditional assembly functions like: Pressure Molding, Vaccume De-aerating, Machining and Turning. I have been leveraging Stratasys systems since 2005 for limited rail car master production. I now have a Bot Farm of 2 - 4th Gen Makerbot 2Xs from the 2013 run with H series motherboards and enhancements that handle my production needs for everything from detail parts, to fine hand railings and end cages, to entire core rail car production. I utilize a mixed medium approach toward function, fit and finish. Real organic materials finish off and serve as my signature for my makes; utilizing everything from hydrocal,, to coal, steel plate, frosted and tinted glass, to aluminum appliques.

bio:
All my models have been printed on a Prusa i3 MK3.

My files are shared for free to show what's capable with low cost 3D printers, and to inspire people to develop a working understanding of how things that may appear very complex at first glance, are actually comprised of many simple parts and concepts, which when combined look more complex than they really are.

The files are licensed under the Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial. Please respect this and do not resell or use my models for any commercial purposes without contacting me first.

I have had several requests for my original model files. I am not releasing them at this time.

Vernier Software & Technology is a maker of science and technology education tools, including data-logging interfaces and a multitude of sensors used in school science classes. Our data-logging/analysis software is used to conduct experiments and analyze the results.

Here on Thingiverse, we will be sharing some designs of our own and creating collections from other's designs that we feel are of interest to the Vernier community. These may range from special mounting brackets, adapters, or hardware to objects used in experiments. We will occasionally browse Thingiverse for designs that are of interest to science educators and add them to our collections in each science area (physics, engineering, biology, etc.)

If you post a design of your own (on your personal Thingiverse space) and feel it would be of interest to Vernier users, you may wish to tag it with "VernierST" so that we can find it easily. Perhaps we will add it to our collections. This is an easy way to share your designs with the Vernier community worldwide. Thingiverse is all about sharing. In this case, it's about enhancing science education through sharing of various printed science widgets. We hope this will create new opportunities for science experimenters and teachers everywhere.

All Vernier-created designs will be tested here before release, but items in our collections may not have been tested -- so proceed with the usual caution.

Makers Manifesto

  1. If it's broken, fix it! Because everyday practical problem solving is the most beautiful form of creativity there is.

  2. If it's not broken, improve it. A small, clever tweak can improve how something works for years to come.

  3. Fixing means freedom and independence. As a fixer, you don't need to worry about wear and tear. Nothing stays new, so forget perfection.

  4. Don’t let companies treat you as a passive consumer. Every time we spend money, we vote for the kinds of products we want to see succeed. Buy products that can be repaired.

  5. A fixed thing is a beautiful thing. Every fix, whether skillful or improvised, holds a story.

  6. If you have an idea, start small and make it good. If it’s right, it'll grow from there.

  7. Nurture your curiosity. keep trying things you've never tried before. It's good for your brain and your soul. Don't be afraid to fail— it makes success all the sweeter.

  8. People are infinitely diverse. Products should be too. Everything can be improved or customized.

9.Share your ideas, your enthusiasm and your skills. If you've found the joy of fixing, pass it on. It's a gift for life.

  1. CREATE, MAKE, ENJOY!

I am a professional 3d artist, toy/game/science education designer, and inventor. I've had over 20 years in the industry making video games and educational software. I've trained Marine Snipers, Astronauts, Coast Guard, Navy crewmen and Kids with FIRST robotics. I've worked on 18 shipped video games, including Geist for Game Cube, Skylanders for 3DS, Call Of Duty for DS, Tron DS, and the First Star Wars Force Unleashed for the DS.

Currently, I'm working a the Institute for Simulation and Training, where I am studying Voxel based 3d generative design for 3d printing on the polyjet Stratasys J750.

I am currently the Director of Generative Design at the PD3d lab.

My Website is www.UniCronStudios.com and I have a Web Comic at www.pirate-cats.com
